DeviceGroup.comment: Add Mail Gateways to this group by applying the Device Tag "MAIL-GW" to the appropriate ExtraHop Devices.A Mail Gateway is a network device typically found at the network edge that carries email messages in and/or out of the organization. This Device Group is a Metric Source for the Dashboards included in the Microsoft Exchange Bundle. The Microsoft Exchange Bundle was designed for Microsoft Exchange Server 2010.Examples of devices that can act as Mail Gateways include appliances designed for mail content scanning/inspection but can also include Routers, Layer-3 Switches, Load Balancers, Proxy Servers, Firewalls.
DeviceGroup.name: Mail Gateways

DeviceGroup.comment: Add Mail Retention Devices to this group by applying the Device Tag "MAIL-AR" to the appropriate ExtraHop Devices.Mail Retention services are often provided by a server-like appliance that receives a copy of every message that is sent and/or received within the organization and to/from the internet.This Device Group is a Metric Source for the Dashboards included in the Microsoft Exchange Bundle. The Microsoft Exchange Bundle was designed for Microsoft Exchange Server 2010.Examples of Mail Retention devices include appliances, servers, mailbox databases, or storage pools used for Exchange mail journaling, archival, and long-term retention.

###When is SMTP used?

SMTP is the primary transfer protocol used to transmit mail messages between two end-points. It is, at its core, a plain-text protocol, but is often encrypted before transit.

While much of the world continues to move towards web-based or thick client email that does not directly leverage SMTP on a per user basis, those systems still rely completely on SMTP for transmitting messages. 

A user sending email via gmail, for instance, is not directly transmitting anything via SMTP from their client computer to the gmail servers. This is handled via HTTPS, as is expected in a webmail environment. Google's mail servers, however, are using SMTP to transmit those messages to the appropriate recipients.

It is also worth noting that the vast majority of email sent today is auto-generated, either sent directly via a web-server or an automated process on an application server. These systems will all transfer their messages via SMTP directly. Not to mention any local mail servers a company may be running that will also send and receive large amounts of SMTP traffic.

As such, having granular, detailed metrics around SMTP behaviors and health in your environment can be powerful aids in maintaining user experience and productivity.

###What is SMTP?

SMTP is a connection-oriented, text-based protocol in which a mail sender communicates with a mail receiver by issuing command strings and supplying necessary data, typically over a TCP connection. 

An SMTP session consists of commands originated by an SMTP client (the sender) and responses from the SMTP server (the receiver). A session may include zero or more SMTP transactions. An SMTP transaction consists of three command/reply sequences (see example below.) They are:

MAIL command, to establish the return address, bounce address, mfrom, or envelope sender. This is the address to which bounce messages should be sent.

RCPT command, to establish a recipient of this message. This command can be issued multiple times, one for each recipient. These addresses are also part of the envelope.

DATA to signal the beginning of the message text; the content of the message, as opposed to its envelope. It consists of a message header and a message body separated by an empty line. DATA is actually a group of commands, and the server replies twice: once to the DATA command proper, to acknowledge that it is ready to receive the text, and the second time after the end-of-data sequence, to either accept or reject the entire message.

Besides the intermediate reply for DATA, each server's reply can be either positive (2xx reply codes) or negative. Negative replies can be permanent (5xx codes) or transient (4xx codes). A reject is a permanent failure by an SMTP server; in this case the SMTP client should send a bounce message. A drop is a positive response followed by message discard rather than delivery.

###User Activity Information

####Encrypted vs. Unencrypted Sessions
Email encryption uses a secure key to encrypt/decrypt mail messages at the server, allowing for secure transactions. This is increasingly standard practice to prevent sensitive information from being compromised in flight.

Note the difference between the number of sessions and the number of encrypted sessions in the chart to the left. That delta is the number of SMTP sessions that are *not* encrypted.

---

####Requests by Client IP
Knowing who is making use of your smtp servers is critical. Whether you're watching for unwanted traffic from a rogue source, or simply ensuring proper user behavior, this information is central to your mail management planning. Any large spikes are worth investigating.

It is important to note here that the number of SMTP requests is not a one to one relationship with the number of emails being sent. Given that each email sent requires several SMTP commands to be issued (more detail in the region below) there will be many more SMTP transactions than actual emails sent from a given environment. This is as expected.

---

####Server Processing Time
Different requests and interactions take varying time to process at on the smtp server. Generally some fluctuation here is expected. Large or repeated spikes, however, could indicate attempted overloading of the mail servers, malicious spamming attempts, compromised client systems acting as mail bots, etc.

---

####Round Trip Time
Mail performance is largely based on desired behavior, I.E. users sending 20MB attachments will see slower performance, and latency. Proper smtp use requires minimal server processing. Should users experience issues and report in to a call center, latency to the client system could easily result in a delayed experience.

##SMTP Method Details

**ehlo or helo:** Sent from SMTP client to server. Occurs immediately after TCP session initiation. Alerts SMTP server of client's intent to transmit SMTP data. Server responds with a status of 250 "OK" and a list of supported SMTP extensions.


**starttls:** Optional command to signal encryption for all future SMTP communication for this session. The client initiates, the server responds, and the key exchange and encryption occurs.



**Auth:** Not listed as a method, but the authentication process occurs post helo (and starttls, if applicable) to authenticate a client as authorized to transfer mail through the connected SMTP server.

**mail:** "mail" is actually "mail from", which is the command used to define the sender address of the given transaction. It is also the method used to signify to the SMTP server that a new mail transaction is about to begin. This initiates a reset of buffers, state tables, etc. 

**rcpt:** "rcpt", which is actually "rcpt to" Defines the recipient of the message. This is the email address to which you want the mail message to be delivered. Note that this command can be repeated many times in a given transaction if a message is destined for multiple recipients.

**data:** After defining the recipient, the data command is sent which signifies that it is time to include the actual body of the mail message. This is sent as a multi-line text string including headers (From, Subject, Content-Transfer-Encoding, To, X-Priority, etc.) as well as the message itself. The last line of the data portion is a period on a line by itself, signifying the end of the message.

**quit:** The quit commend is the last command sent during a normal smtp exchange. This signifies that the transaction is finished and the client is ready to terminate the connection.

**rset:** This command is used to abort the current smtp transaction. If it is issued the connection to the mail server will not be closed, but all information established in the current SMTP transaction (sender, recipients, mail data, etc.) will be abandoned and buffers and state tables will be cleared.

## Message Rates
___

###SMTP Error Codes

With SMTP it is important to remember that first, there will be many errors. This is not something to be alarmed about. Unlike many protocols, errors are a natural part of SMTP for multiple reasons. 

First, it is common for mis-typed or out of date email addresses to cause many errors to cause the error count to seem unusually high. Second, given SMTP's natural tendency towards attempting to re-send failed messages several times before giving up, a single error can effectively show up multiple times (once for each subsequent attempt). Last, but not least, many of the errors received deal with an inability to deliver a message (mailbox full, incorrect address, no permission to deliver, etc.) rather than an actual protocol failure. 

Some of the relevant SMTP error codes are:


**422:** The recipient's mailbox has exceeded its storage limit.

**431:** Not enough space on the disk, or an "out of memory" condition due to a file overload.

**500:** A syntax error: the server couldn't recognize the command.

**503:** The server has encountered a bad sequence of commands, or it requires an authentication.

**510:** Bad email address.

**550:** It usually defines a non-existent email address on the remote side.

**552:** "Requested mail actions aborted – Exceeded storage allocation": simply put, the recipient's mailbox has exceeded its limits.

**553:** "Requested action not taken – Mailbox name invalid". That is, there's an incorrect email address into the recipients line. 

**554:** This means that the transaction has failed. It's a permanent error and the server will not try to send the message again.

### Mail Flow: SMTP Errors

These widgets track inbound and outbound SMTP errors from servers and network devices responsible for mail delivery.

Note that directionality of mail flow is not represented here, as devices act as both SMTP Servers and SMTP Clients, and that the peer device for a given flow may be inside or outside this organization.

* SMTP Server Errors represent errors SENT by the machine back to one of it's SMTP clients.

* SMTP Client Errors represnet errors RECIEVED by the machine from it's SMTP servers.

## Network Performance
___

These charts use TCP Round Trip Time to indicate network performance for this device group: the speed at which the network is able to deliver the content transmitted by these servers.

**Top Left:** The 95th percentile can be considered the 'high water mark'. While it excludes sporadic outliers (including the 'maximum' RTT), the 95th percentile indicates that 95% of transactions fall below this observed RTT measurement.

**Top Right:** This chart shows TCP Round Trip Time consistency for the selected time interval. Each point in time measurement contains a five-tuple dataset that includes the 5th, 25th, 50th, 755h, and 95th percentile.

**Bottom Left:** This chart looks at the average (mean) Round Trip Time for each member of this Device Group. At a glance, it is easy to see if all group members are seeing similar network performance, or if there are standouts.

**Bottom Right:** This chart shows an overall Round Trip Time performance sampleset for the entire selected time interval, including the 5th, 25th, 50th, 755h, and 95th percentile. Compare to a different time interval using the time selector.

## Packet Loss
____

These charts show packet loss rates for flows inbound to, and outbound from, this Device Group's members, and when they happened during the selected time interval.

The bar graphs indicate what group members and application protocols are experiencing the most drops in and out.

# Hub Transport Servers
___

This dashboard looks at the health and performance of Exchange Hub Transport Servers (HUB).

Hub Transport Servers handle all mail flow inside the organization and deliver mail to a recipient's mailbox. Hub Transport Servers also journal messages to mail archivers and can relay mail through a third party smart host.

More About Hub Transport Servers:
* [Overview of the Hub Transport Server Role](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb123494.aspx)
* [Understanding Back Pressure](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb201658.aspx)
* [Understanding Receive Connectors](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa996395.aspx)
* [TechNet: Exchange for IT Pros](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/office/dn788775)

# Client Access Servers
___

This dashboard looks at the health and performance of Exchange Client Access Servers.

The Client Access Server (CAS) handles all client connections to Exchange Server (including Outlook (MAPI and RPC/HTTP), mobile (ActiveSync), web (OWA), and 3rd party POP3 and IMAP4 clients).

More About Client Access Servers:

# Mailbox Servers
___

This dashboard looks at the health and performance of Exchange Mailbox Servers.

The Mailbox server role hosts mailbox and public folder databases. It also generates the offline address book (OAB). Mailbox servers provide services that calculate e-mail address policies and address lists for recipients and enforce managed folders.

More About Mailbox Servers:
* [Understanding Mailbox](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ee694812.aspx)
* [Overview of the Mailbox Server Role](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb124699.aspx)
* [Managing Mailbox Servers](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb123480.aspx)
* [Error and Event Reference for Mailbox Servers](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dd298018.aspx)
* [TechNet: Exchange for IT Pros](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/office/dn788775)

### Server & Network Issues

Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) is the framework that sits between the Applications running on a host and the Network that delivers application transactions between application servers, and between servers and clients. 

In short, TCP is where the Application meets the Network. We can use TCP to detect issues that reside 
* on the Application Servers themselves
* on the Network 

and thereby assist with fault isolation.


See **Additional Resources** below to learn how Extrahop observes and analyzes TCP health in real time, and for which TCP metrics are best to track as indicators of host and network problems.

## Network Performance
___

These charts use TCP Round Trip Time to indicate network performance for this device group: the speed at which the network is able to deliver the content transmitted by these servers.

**Top Left:** The 95th percentile can be considered the 'high water mark'. While it excludes sporadic outliers (including the 'maximum' RTT), the 95th percentile indicates that 95% of transactions fall below this observed RTT measurement.

**Top Right:** This chart shows TCP Round Trip Time consistency for the selected time interval. Each point in time measurement contains a five-tuple dataset that includes the 5th, 25th, 50th, 755h, and 95th percentile.

**Bottom Left:** This chart looks at the average (mean) Round Trip Time for each member of this Device Group. At a glance, it is easy to see if all group members are seeing similar network performance, or if there are standouts.

**Bottom Right:** This chart shows an overall Round Trip Time performance sampleset for the entire selected time interval, including the 5th, 25th, 50th, 755h, and 95th percentile. Compare to a different time interval using the time selector.

## Packet Loss
____

These charts show packet loss rates for flows inbound to, and outbound from, this Device Group's members, and when they happened during the selected time interval.

The bar graphs indicate what group members and application protocols are experiencing the most drops in and out.

### Mail Flow: Throughput

This widget tracks raw bytes of SMTP traffic in and out of the systems that are responsible for receiving and sending mail, including Microsoft Exchange Servers and network devices like Mail Gateways.

Note that directionality of mail flow is not represented here. 

For example, SMTP bytes OUT from an Edge Transport Server to a Hub Transport Server may represent mail that is INBOUND from another organization. 

Similarly SMTP bytes OUT from an Edge Transport Server to another domain's Mail Exchanger would represent mail OUTBOUND from this organization.

### Autodiscover Service

The Exchange Autodiscover Service allows Exchange users to quickly confgigure their client devices without having an Exchange administrator provide specialized instructions.

The Autodiscover Service relies on DNS Service (SRV) records as well as HTTP-published XML files. Extrahop is able to identify and analyze DNS-related and HTTP-related Autodiscover transactions.
